args: So this is the royal family library. I was\nnever permitted to enter back in my day,\neven in the seat of court magician.

That is because part of its purpose is to
seal away that which cannot be glimpsed
by the public eye. Only a few outside each
generation's rulers have been inside.
It's a place where all the royal family's\nskeletons are interred, in other words.
It is distasteful, but undeniable. The place\nought to never have existed to begin with.
Well, a royal dynasty isn't all kissing\nbabies and cutting ribbons. In any event,\nlet's make good use of the place now.
Agreed. Let's start by looking for anything\non Nedrick and Beren.
It would be most expeditious if we could\nfind something written by Aurelius at the\ntime.
I'd wager that's a lost cause. Still,\nlet's give the place a good look, in the\nunlikely event we find ourselves fortunate.
*sigh* No such luck. There's nothing in\nany of these records save formal matters.

Some mention the fifth scion's power
being judged a danger and seeking the
Faerie Kingdom's help with the critically
ill seventh scion, but...
...that's not what you're looking to find\nout, is it?
No. I already know what happened in the\npast here in this world.
What I don't understand is what Aurelius\nwas thinking at the time; why he made the\njudgments he did about Beren and Nedrick.
By all appearances, it is as though he\nhimself was trying to sow the seeds of\nchaos. His actions almost defy reason.

I am thus forced to believe that there was
something that went beyond pure reason.
I thought perhaps I could learn what that
something was here.

The Aurelius I know wasn't the sort of man
so given to introspection that he would
record his personal feelings. Are you
different?
A fair point. Perhaps I ought to start by\nlamenting my own indolence, then.
What's our next move? There are still\ncountless books we've not checked.\nWill we continue searching?

No, I suspect that will prove meaningless.
Even if we were to search more, we'd
likely only come across records from
hundreds of years ago.
Even so, this was no fruitless effort.\nI've found something deeply fascinating.

This book here. I've only given it a quick
scan, but it seems to have written in it a
means for the temporary sharing of
memory and consciousness with a dragon.
From what I can tell, it seems to be a type\nof simple pact.
Let's have a look, shall we? Mhm... I see.\nIn this kingdom, one has not the right to\nbecome ruler without a dragonpact. But...

Right. Not everyone born to the royal
family can forge a pact. There were likely
some among the rulers of the past who
used this technique to deceive.
A king assuming his station without the\nsovereign right... Certainly this counts as\na skeleton in the royal family's closet.
But what do you hope to do with this?\nSurely it's a little late for you to acquire\nthe right to become a king.
Indeed. What catches my interest is the\npart about sharing consciousness with\na dragon.
Like this world's Zodiark, for instance.
Zodiark? Why would you want to—oh!
The Aurelius of this world turned to mana\nand became one with Zodiark after his\ndeath.
Thus, if I used this technique to connect\nwith the fell dragon, I could know what\nAurelius himself once thought.
With this decided, I will be returning to the\nHalidom. I must meet with Zodiark quickly.
Wait. Are you sure about this? To put\nit plainly, I don't think it's a good idea.
Why do you say that? Speak.
You're an Aurelius from another world.\nAnd the Aurelius of this world has long\nsince passed on.
What of it? Why now do you bring up\nthings already evident?
Because you don't understand a single\nthing about yourself.
Listen to me. Right now, the fact that there\nis an Aurelius in this world is, in essence,\na paradox.

If my thinking is correct, some sort of
general principle must be at work in the
world—something that works to repair
such incidences.
In other words, I would not be surprised\nin the slightest if you were at some point\nexcised from this world entirely.
But right now, you are severed from the\nchain of causality—even your very link\nto the world has been cut.
As a result, you've come unstitched from\nthose natural principles. And that is what\nprotects you from being summarily erased.

You said that sharing consciousness with
Zodiark would be a form of pact. It is
possible you could be connected to the
underpinnings of natural order through it.
Not even I know what might happen to\nyour body in such an event.
But one thing is certain: the world would\nspring into action to see you expunged.
Heh. The mere sound of that strikes fear\ninto the heart.
Audric! I'm not joking. It's always been a\nbad habit of yours to make light of your\nown well-being.
Ah, forgive me. I did not think you were\njoking. But...can this ＂principle＂ you\ndescribe be resisted somehow?
I'm afraid that's impossible. It is, so to\nspeak, a universal rule of the world.
Then there's no use fretting over it.\nI will take the actions I think I must.\nNo more, no less.
...Honestly, I forgot what an impossible\nman you are. Aurelius was the same way,\nfor as long as I can remember.
I'm sure you were plenty of trouble for the\nCassandra in your world, too.
Indeed. I left her a debt I can never repay.
Then do me a favor and don't try to pay\nit forward to me.
While I've never heard the specifics from\nyou, I assume that the me in the other\nworld died smiling, yes?
Er... Well, yes. Yes, she did.\nYou knew that, did you?
How could I not, my dear man?
